AGI - Iran's supreme leader, ayatollah Ali Khamenei, warned Israel that it will regret having made a deadly attack on the Iranian consulate in Damascus on Monday. CNN reports it. "With the help of God, we will make sure that the Zionists repent of their crime of aggression against the Iranian consulate in Damascus," said Khamenei in a morning post on X in Hebrew. Iran promised to avenge itself after accusing Israel of bombing its embassies complex in the capital of Syria, in a mortal escalation of regional tensions on the war in Gaza which once again seems to increase the risk of a wider conflict in the Middle East. The air strike destroyed the consulate building in the Syrian capital, killing at least seven officials, including Mohammed Reza Zahedi, a high commander of the Iranian revolutionary Guards (IRGC), and senior commander Mohammad Hadi Haji Rahimi, according to the Iranian Foreign Ministry. The Israeli army told CNN not to comment on foreign reports. However, a military spokesman said that Israel believes that the target was a "military building of the Quds forces", a unit of the IRC responsible for operations abroad.&nbsp;
